data.content:
Here's the complete migration analysis and replacement code for your `EventProcessor`.

## Pattern Classification

| API | Pattern | Replacement |
|-----|---------|-------------|
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Blocking call interruption — wakes thread from `WaitOne()` | `CancellationToken.WaitHandle` via `WaitHandle.WaitAny` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | Forcible termination after timeout | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` — cooperative cancellation |
| `while (true)` | Cancellable work loop | Loop on `!token.IsCancellationRequested` |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new ManualResetEvent(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new Queue<string>();
    private readonly object _lock = new object();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;
        var handles = new[] { _newEvent, token.WaitHandle };

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Wakes on EITHER a new event OR cancellation — replaces
            // Thread.Interrupt which threw ThreadInterruptedException.
            int signaled = WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);

            if (signaled == 1) // CancellationToken.WaitHandle fired
                break;

            _newEvent.Reset();

            // Drain all queued items — fixes a race in the original
            // where multiple Enqueue calls between WaitOne/Reset
            // would only process one item per wakeup.
            while (true)
            {
                string? item;
                lock (_lock)
                {
                    if (_queue.Count == 0)
                        break;
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
                }
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        // Signal the token — wakes the thread from WaitAny immediately.
        // No Interrupt or Abort needed.
        _cts.Cancel();
        _thread?.Join(5000);
        // If the thread is STILL alive after 5s, it means Handle()
        // is stuck in uncooperative code. See pitfall #3 below.
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

## Key Changes

1. **`Thread.Interrupt()` → `WaitHandle.WaitAny`** — The cancellation token's `WaitHandle` participates in the same wait, so the thread wakes instantly on cancel without needing `Interrupt` (obsolete: `SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9).

2. **`Thread.Abort()` → `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()`** — `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+. Cooperative cancellation via the token replaces it.

3. **`while (true)` → `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)`** — The loop voluntarily exits when cancellation is requested.

4. **Bug fix: drain loop** — The original had a race condition: multiple rapid `Enqueue` calls before `Reset()` would lose signals, processing only one item per wakeup. The inner `while` loop now drains the queue.

5. **`IDisposable`** — `CancellationTokenSource` and `ManualResetEvent` are disposable. Leaking them causes timer/callback leaks.

## Pitfalls To Watch

| # | Pitfall | Mitigation |
|---|---------|------------|
| 1 | **`Handle()` never checks the token** — cancellation only takes effect between items, not mid-processing | If `Handle()` does long work, pass `_cts.Token` into it and call `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints |
| 2 | **`Handle()` blocks on synchronous I/O** — `socket.Read()`, `File.ReadAllBytes()`, etc. won't respond to the token | Replace with async overloads that accept `CancellationToken`, or set read timeouts |
| 3 | **No equivalent to `Abort()` for truly stuck threads** — if `Join(5000)` times out, you have no kill switch | Move uncooperative work to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()` as a last resort |
| 4 | **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** — causes callback/timer leaks | Always wrap in `using` or implement `IDisposable` as shown |
| 5 | **Double-`Stop()` race** — calling `Stop()` twice will call `Cancel()` on an already-cancelled/disposed source | Guard with a `volatile bool _stopped` flag or use `Interlocked.Exchange` |

## Optional Modernization (not required for migration)

If you want to go fully async, replace the entire class with a `Channel<string>`:

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _worker;

    public void Start() =>
        _worker = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken token)
    {
        await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(token))
            Handle(item);
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item) =>
        _channel.Writer.TryWrite(item);

    public async Task StopAsync()
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();
        _cts.CancelAfter(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
        if (_worker is not null)
            await _worker;
    }

    public void Dispose() => _cts.Dispose();
    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

This is **optional** — the synchronous version above compiles and runs correctly on .NET 8. The `Channel<T>` version eliminates the manual `WaitHandle`/lock/queue entirely.
